#ThrowbackThursday - Star Trails over Arch Rock, Joshua Tree National Park, California, USA
.
Canon EOS-1V, EF16-35mm lens; first exposure f/2.8 for 1/8 second; second exposure f/2.8 for 5 hours; Fujichrome Provia film; October 1998
.
To achieve this image of star trails above Arch Rock, I had to take two exposures. A single exposure of just the stars would outline the arch as a black silhouette, which was not what I wanted. During the first exposure I used a polarizer to darken the sky to nearly black, while underexposing the arch by one stop. The arch was illuminated by the lingering afterglow of sunset. I ate my dinner while the light faded and later took the second exposure, this time leaving the shutter open for five hours, more than enough time to allow the stars to move across the night sky. In 1998 I had less worries
 of satellite trails marring the image as well. How things have changed!
.
I used the widest aperture that the lens permitted and kept the f-stops the same. Had I used an f/16 in the first exposure and an f/2.8 in the second, a slight shift could occur in the composition, resulting in the stars overlapping the rock's edge.

Being published this week is author/photographer @graeme.green 's The New Big 5: A Global Photography Project for Endangered Wildlife. Over five years ago he contacted us about an idea he had about creating a new Big Five of wildlife photography. The Big Five was a term coined by game hunters and includes the African lion, leopard, rhino, elephant, and buffalo. Graeme took this phrase and has turned it on its head. In his book being published on April 4th, he has brought together 165 wildlife photographers (including me) and conservationists to raise awareness of the crucial issues facing the world’s wildlife.

Order your copy today !

https://www.amazon.com/New-Big-Photography-Project-Endangered/dp/1647228700

Word of the day: psammophile

Spelled correctly by the winner of this year's national spelling bee, psammophile refers to an animal that thrives in a sandy environment, such as this adder that lives in the desert of Namibia.

In a win for wildlife and indigenous communities, the last remaining oil and gas leases on the coastal plain of the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge have been cancelled. The US is on track to produce more oil and natural gas than ever before and tapping this vital ecological sanctuary was always a bad idea.

Called “the place where life begins” by the Yup’ik and Gwich’in, the refuge is home to 250 animal species including vast herds of caribou that migrate from wintering Canada every year to calve on the coastal plain, grizzlies, wolves, and millions of migratory birds from as far as Antarctica. As long as I have been photographing, which is a long time indeed, it has been the focus of heated debate over resource extraction. One thing we should know is that this ban is not permanent, and more advocacy must be done to make sure this biologically rich area remains wild and untouched forever—a gift to future generations.

Wild Lives is available now - order your signed copy in time for the Holidays! 

Wild Lives presents a celebration of the beauty, ferocity, and revival of Earth’s endangered wildlife through the lens of legendary photographer Art Wolfe and the words of author Gregory Green.
Wild Lives explores the extraordinary diversity of species that inhabit the planet. Some are common, some rare, and many are conservation success stories, species that have been brought back from the edge of extinction. Over his forty-year career, Art Wolfe has photographed many species that were once on endangered species lists, but are now flourishing (such as the bald eagle and humpback whale). These recoveries are an uplifting testament to the resilience of life when it is given a chance.
